{
  "monologue": "The user is near baseline structure but needs a small, low-effort nudge to push toward steadier post-meal control. Their profile shows high sensitivity to stress and a strong need for fixed routines, so a tiny, wrap-up cue after the meal ritual can enhance automaticity without adding complexity. This leverages habit formation principles (cue + small action) and reduces post-meal rumination, nudging behavior gradually toward the target level without demanding a big change.",
  "utterance": "A simple next step: after your meal routine, add a 60-second wrap-up. In that minute, name one thing you genuinely appreciated about the meal, and identify one tiny non-food action you will do in the next two minutes if cravings arise (for example, a quick stretch, a glass of water, or tidying a small area). Repeat this wrap-up consistently for the next three days. This small, fixed cue supports mood stability and strengthens your post-meal routine toward your goal with minimal extra effort.",
  "endkey": false
}
